GCN Step-by-Step:

This is the second notebook for the GNN learning with movie dataset.

This notebook shows exactly what happens inside a GCN layer using your actual MovieLens data. We will not focus on the training step, however we will have a deep understanding about what happens in GCN layer.

You can see what's happening inside GCN layer after step 7.

  • Step 1: Load Actual MovieLens Data

      Total ratings: 100836
  Total users: 610
  Total movies: 9724

  • Step 2: Create a TINY Subset for Understanding

      TOTAL: 3 users + 10 movies = 13 nodes

  • Step 3: Build the Edge List (Who is Connected to Whom)

      Example:

  Edge 0: Node 0 (User) -> Node 3 (Movie)
  Edge 1: Node 3 (Movie) -> Node 0 (User)
  Edge 2: Node 0 (User) -> Node 4 (Movie)
  Edge 3: Node 4 (Movie) -> Node 0 (User)

  • Step 4: Find Neighbors for Each Node

      Node 2 (User 5):
    Neighbors (node indices): [np.int64(3), np.int64(7), np.int64(10)]
    Neighbors (movies): ["'Toy Story (1995)'", "'Usual Suspects, The '", "'Braveheart (1995)'"]
    Degree (# of neighbors): 3

  • Step 5: Initialize Node Embeddings

      --- USER EMBEDDINGS ---
  Node 0 (User 1): [ 0.248 -0.069  0.324  0.762]
  Node 1 (User 4): [-0.117 -0.117  0.79   0.384]

  --- MOVIE EMBEDDINGS ---
  Node 3 ('Toy Story (1995)'): [ 0.121 -0.957 -0.862 -0.281]
  Node 4 ('Grumpier Old Men (19'): [-0.506  0.157 -0.454 -0.706]

  • Step 7: GCN LAYER - The Main Computation!

  • STEP 7.1: Get neighbor embeddings

      Example:
  Node 4 ('Grumpier Old Men (1995)'): [-0.506  0.157 -0.454 -0.706]
  Node 5 ('Heat (1995)'): [ 0.733 -0.113  0.034 -0.712]

  • STEP 7.2: Normalize by degree

      Example:
   Node 4 ('Grumpier Old Men (19'):
      Original h_u:    [-0.506  0.157 -0.454 -0.706]
      degree[u] = 1, degree[v] = 10
      norm_factor = sqrt(1  10) = sqrt(10) = 3.162
      Normalized h_u:  [-0.16   0.05  -0.144 -0.223]

  • STEP 7.3: Sum normalized embeddings

      = [-0.095 -1.071 -0.636 -0.352]

  • STEP 7.4: Apply weight matrix W

      Weight matrix W (shape: (4, 4)):
  [[-0.338  0.306  0.515  0.466]
   [-0.42  -0.155  0.166  0.488]
   [-0.24  -0.093 -0.553 -0.598]
   [ 0.406  0.678 -0.036  0.502]]

  Matrix multiplication: W @ aggregated
    (4, 4) @ (4,) = (4,)

  • STEP 7.5: Add bias

  • STEP 7.6: Apply ReLU activation

  • Step 8: Do This For ALL Nodes

      APPLYING GCN LAYER TO ALL NODES
  ======================================================================
  Node  0 (User 1                   ): [ 0.248 -0.069  0.324  0.762] -> [0.    0.    0.721 0.   ]
  Node  1 (User 4                   ): [-0.117 -0.117  0.79   0.384] -> [0.    0.008 0.224 0.184]

  • Step 9: Split Into User and Movie Embeddings

  • Step 10: Predict a Rating!

      Dot product (element-wise multiply then sum):
    [0.    0.    0.721 0.   ]
   [0.103 0.    0.004 0.241]
  = [0.    0.    0.003 0.   ]

Let's analyze the data at first.

# Visualize a small subgraph
def visualize_subgraph(df, num_users_to_show=10, num_movies_to_show=20):
    """
    Visualize a small portion of the user-movie graph.
    """
    # Select top users by number of ratings
    top_users = df.groupby('userId').size().nlargest(num_users_to_show).index.tolist()

    # Get their rated movies
    subset_df = df[df['userId'].isin(top_users)]
    top_movies = subset_df.groupby('movieId').size().nlargest(num_movies_to_show).index.tolist()

    # Filter to only these users and movies
    viz_df = subset_df[subset_df['movieId'].isin(top_movies)]

    # Create NetworkX graph
    G = nx.Graph()

    # Add user nodes
    for user in viz_df['userId'].unique():
        G.add_node(f"U{user}", node_type='user')

    # Add movie nodes
    for movie in viz_df['movieId'].unique():
        title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie]['title'].values[0][:20]
        G.add_node(f"M{movie}", node_type='movie', title=title)

    # Add edges with ratings
    for _, row in viz_df.iterrows():
        G.add_edge(f"U{row['userId']}", f"M{row['movieId']}", rating=row['rating'])

    # Draw the graph
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 10))

    # Position nodes
    pos = nx.bipartite_layout(G,
                              [n for n in G.nodes() if n.startswith('U')],
                              align='horizontal')

    # Color nodes by type
    user_nodes = [n for n in G.nodes() if n.startswith('U')]
    movie_nodes = [n for n in G.nodes() if n.startswith('M')]

    # Draw
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, nodelist=user_nodes, node_color='steelblue',
                          node_size=500, alpha=0.8, label='Users')
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, nodelist=movie_nodes, node_color='coral',
                          node_size=500, alpha=0.8, label='Movies')

    # Edge colors based on rating
    edge_colors = [G[u][v]['rating'] for u, v in G.edges()]
    edges = nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edge_color=edge_colors,
                                   edge_cmap=plt.cm.RdYlGn, width=1.5, alpha=0.6)

    # Labels
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, font_size=8)

    plt.colorbar(edges, label='Rating')
    plt.legend(loc='upper left')
    plt.title('User-Movie Bipartite Graph (Subgraph Visualization)\n'
              'Blue = Users, Orange = Movies, Edge Color = Rating')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    return G

subgraph = visualize_subgraph(df_ratings)

# Interactive visualization with Plotly
def interactive_graph_viz(df, num_users=15, num_movies=30):
    """
    Create an interactive visualization using Plotly.
    """
    # Select subset
    top_users = df.groupby('userId').size().nlargest(num_users).index.tolist()
    subset_df = df[df['userId'].isin(top_users)]
    top_movies = subset_df.groupby('movieId').size().nlargest(num_movies).index.tolist()
    viz_df = subset_df[subset_df['movieId'].isin(top_movies)]

    # Create graph
    G = nx.Graph()
    for user in viz_df['userId'].unique():
        G.add_node(f"U{user}", node_type='user')
    for movie in viz_df['movieId'].unique():
        title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie]['title'].values[0]
        G.add_node(f"M{movie}", node_type='movie', title=title)
    for _, row in viz_df.iterrows():
        G.add_edge(f"U{row['userId']}", f"M{row['movieId']}", rating=row['rating'])

    # Layout
    pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=2, iterations=50, seed=42)

    # Extract positions
    edge_x, edge_y = [], []
    for edge in G.edges():
        x0, y0 = pos[edge[0]]
        x1, y1 = pos[edge[1]]
        edge_x.extend([x0, x1, None])
        edge_y.extend([y0, y1, None])

    edge_trace = go.Scatter(
        x=edge_x, y=edge_y,
        line=dict(width=0.5, color='#888'),
        hoverinfo='none',
        mode='lines'
    )

    # Node positions
    node_x, node_y, node_text, node_color = [], [], [], []
    for node in G.nodes():
        x, y = pos[node]
        node_x.append(x)
        node_y.append(y)
        if node.startswith('U'):
            node_text.append(f"User {node[1:]}\nRatings: {G.degree(node)}")
            node_color.append(0)
        else:
            title = G.nodes[node].get('title', 'Unknown')
            node_text.append(f"{title}\nRatings: {G.degree(node)}")
            node_color.append(1)

    node_trace = go.Scatter(
        x=node_x, y=node_y,
        mode='markers',
        hoverinfo='text',
        text=node_text,
        marker=dict(
            showscale=False,
            color=node_color,
            colorscale=[[0, 'steelblue'], [1, 'coral']],
            size=15,
            line_width=2
        )
    )

    fig = go.Figure(data=[edge_trace, node_trace],
                   layout=go.Layout(
                       title='Interactive User-Movie Graph',
                       #titlefont_size=16,
                       showlegend=False,
                       hovermode='closest',
                       xaxis=dict(showgrid=False, zeroline=False, showticklabels=False),
                       yaxis=dict(showgrid=False, zeroline=False, showticklabels=False)
                   ))
    fig.show()

# Create mappings: original IDs -> 0, 1, 2, ...
unique_users = sorted(small_df['userId'].unique())
unique_movies = sorted(small_df['movieId'].unique())

user_to_idx = {user: idx for idx, user in enumerate(unique_users)}
movie_to_idx = {movie: idx for idx, movie in enumerate(unique_movies)}

num_users = len(unique_users)
num_movies = len(unique_movies)
num_nodes = num_users + num_movies

print("USER MAPPING (userId -> node index):")
for user, idx in user_to_idx.items():
    print(f"  User {user} -> Node {idx}")

print(f"\nMOVIE MAPPING (movieId -> node index):")
print(f"  (Movie indices start at {num_users} because users come first)")
for movie, idx in movie_to_idx.items():
    movie_title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie]['title'].values[0][:30]
    print(f"  Movie {movie} ({movie_title}...) -> Node {num_users + idx}")

print(f"\n" + "="*50)
print(f"TOTAL: {num_users} users + {num_movies} movies = {num_nodes} nodes")

Step 3: Build the Edge List (Who is Connected to Whom)

Each rating creates an edge: User <-> Movie

In[6]:
# Build edge list from ratings
edges_source = []  # From node
edges_target = []  # To node

print("BUILDING EDGES FROM RATINGS:")
print("="*60)

for _, row in small_df.iterrows():
    user_id = row['userId']
    movie_id = row['movieId']
    rating = row['rating']
    
    # Get node indices
    user_node = user_to_idx[user_id]
    movie_node = num_users + movie_to_idx[movie_id]  # Movies start after users!
    
    # Add bidirectional edges (user->movie AND movie->user)
    edges_source.append(user_node)
    edges_target.append(movie_node)
    
    edges_source.append(movie_node)
    edges_target.append(user_node)
    
    movie_title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie_id]['title'].values[0][:25]
    print(f"Rating: User {user_id} -> Movie '{movie_title}' (rating={rating})")
    print(f"  Creates edge: Node {user_node} <-> Node {movie_node}")
    print()

edges_source = np.array(edges_source)
edges_target = np.array(edges_target)

print(f"\nTotal edges: {len(edges_source)} (bidirectional, so 2x the ratings)")

for node in range(num_users):
    user_id = unique_users[node]
    neighbor_nodes = neighbors[node]

    # Convert neighbor node indices to movie names
    neighbor_movies = []
    for n in neighbor_nodes:
        movie_idx = n - num_users
        movie_id = unique_movies[movie_idx]
        movie_title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie_id]['title'].values[0][:20]
        neighbor_movies.append(f"'{movie_title}'")

    print(f"\nNode {node} (User {user_id}):")
    print(f"  Neighbors (node indices): {neighbor_nodes}")
    print(f"  Neighbors (movies): {neighbor_movies}")
    print(f"  Degree (# of neighbors): {len(neighbor_nodes)}")

print("\n--- MOVIES ---")
for node in range(num_users, num_nodes):
    movie_idx = node - num_users
    movie_id = unique_movies[movie_idx]
    movie_title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie_id]['title'].values[0][:25]

    print(f"  Neighbors (users): {neighbor_users}")
    print(f"  Degree (# of neighbors): {len(neighbor_nodes)}")

    deg_u = degree[n]  # Degree of neighbor
    deg_v = degree[TARGET_NODE]  # Degree of target
    norm_factor = np.sqrt(deg_u * deg_v)

Step 8: Do This For ALL Nodes

Now let's apply the same computation to every node in the graph.

In[22]:
# Apply GCN layer to ALL nodes
print("APPLYING GCN LAYER TO ALL NODES")
print("="*70)

# Storage for new embeddings
new_embeddings = np.zeros_like(embeddings)

for v in range(num_nodes):
    # Get node info for printing
    if v < num_users:
        node_name = f"User {unique_users[v]}"
    else:
        movie_idx = v - num_users
        movie_id = unique_movies[movie_idx]
        node_name = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie_id]['title'].values[0][:25]
    
    # Get neighbors
    neighbor_indices = neighbors[v]
    
    if len(neighbor_indices) == 0:
        # No neighbors - keep original embedding
        new_embeddings[v] = embeddings[v]
        print(f"Node {v} ({node_name}): No neighbors, keeping original")
        continue
    
    # Step 1: Gather and normalize neighbor embeddings
    aggregated = np.zeros(EMBEDDING_DIM)
    for u in neighbor_indices:
        norm_factor = np.sqrt(degree[u] * degree[v])
        aggregated += embeddings[u] / norm_factor
    
    # Step 2: Apply W, bias, ReLU
    transformed = W @ aggregated
    with_bias = transformed + bias
    new_emb = np.maximum(0, with_bias)  # ReLU
    
    new_embeddings[v] = new_emb
    
    print(f"Node {v:2d} ({node_name:25s}): {embeddings[v]} -> {new_emb}")

print("\n" + "="*70)
print("GCN LAYER COMPLETE!")
print(f"Input shape:  ({num_nodes}, {EMBEDDING_DIM})")
print(f"Output shape: ({num_nodes}, {EMBEDDING_DIM})")

    title = df_movies[df_movies['movieId'] == movie_id]['title'].values[0][:30]
    print(f"  {title}: {movie_embeddings[i]}")

Summary: What We Did

1. LOAD DATA
   df_ratings: userId, movieId, rating
   
2. BUILD GRAPH
   - Nodes: Users (0, 1, 2, ...) + Movies (num_users, num_users+1, ...)
   - Edges: From ratings (user-movie connections)
   - Neighbors: Movies a user rated / Users who rated a movie

3. INITIALIZE EMBEDDINGS
   - Random vectors for each node
   - Shape: (num_nodes, embedding_dim)

4. GCN LAYER (for each node v):
   a. Get neighbor embeddings {h_u}
   b. Normalize by degree: h_u / sqrt(deg_u * deg_v)
   c. Sum normalized embeddings
   d. Multiply by weight matrix W
   e. Add bias b
   f. Apply ReLU
   
5. SPLIT EMBEDDINGS
   - User embeddings: first num_users rows
   - Movie embeddings: remaining rows

6. PREDICT RATING
   rating = dot(user_embedding, movie_embedding)

Key Insight: Why This Works

After the GCN layer:

  • User 1's embedding contains information from all movies they rated
  • Movie A's embedding contains information from all users who rated it

So when we compute dot(user_1_emb, movie_A_emb):

  • If User 1 and Movie A share common "taste patterns" high dot product high rating
  • If they don't match low dot product low rating

With multiple layers, information travels further:

  • Layer 1: User knows their movies
  • Layer 2: User knows other users who rated the same movies
  • Layer 3: User knows what movies those other users liked!

This is how GNNs capture "users who liked X also liked Y" patterns!

This is the GCNRecommender Class:

In[]:
# GCN Implementation with shape tracking

from torch_geometric.nn import GCNConv

class GCNRecommender(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_users, num_movies, embedding_dim=64, num_layers=2):
        super().__init__()
        self.num_users = num_users
        self.num_movies = num_movies
        num_nodes = num_users + num_movies

        # Initial embeddings for all nodes
        self.embedding = nn.Embedding(num_nodes, embedding_dim)  # (10334, 64)

        # GCN layers
        self.conv1 = GCNConv(embedding_dim, embedding_dim)  # W: (64, 64)
        self.conv2 = GCNConv(embedding_dim, embedding_dim)  # W: (64, 64)

    def forward(self, edge_index, user_idx, movie_idx, verbose=False):
        # Get all node embeddings
        x = self.embedding.weight  # (10334, 64)
        if verbose: print(f"Initial embeddings: {x.shape}")

        # GCN Layer 1
        x = self.conv1(x, edge_index)  # (10334, 64)  (10334, 64)
        x = torch.relu(x)
        if verbose: print(f"After GCN Layer 1: {x.shape}")

        # GCN Layer 2
        x = self.conv2(x, edge_index)  # (10334, 64)  (10334, 64)
        x = torch.relu(x)
        if verbose: print(f"After GCN Layer 2: {x.shape}")

        # Split into user and movie embeddings
        user_emb = x[:self.num_users]      # (610, 64)
        movie_emb = x[self.num_users:]      # (9724, 64)
        if verbose:
            print(f"User embeddings: {user_emb.shape}")
            print(f"Movie embeddings: {movie_emb.shape}")

        # Predict ratings for specific (user, movie) pairs
        user_vecs = user_emb[user_idx]      # (batch,)  (batch, 64)
        movie_vecs = movie_emb[movie_idx]    # (batch,)  (batch, 64)
        if verbose:
            print(f"Selected user vectors: {user_vecs.shape}")
            print(f"Selected movie vectors: {movie_vecs.shape}")

        # Dot product
        ratings = (user_vecs * movie_vecs).sum(dim=1)  # (batch, 64)  (batch,)
        if verbose: print(f"Output ratings: {ratings.shape}")

        return ratings
